{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-blog-post-js","path":"/the-neovim-setup/","webpackCompilationHash":"70ecb58e0bd2ee025595","result":{"data":{"site":{"siteMetadata":{"title":"Program It Forward","author":"joselevelsup"}},"markdownRemark":{"id":"22acd251-db3d-5976-906e-22c4fd3c09d0","excerpt":"The Setup Previously, I had spoken about my adventures of going through different code editors and how it brought me to my current code editor, Neovim. Well…","html":"<h1>The Setup</h1>\n<p>Previously, I had spoken about my adventures of going through different code editors and how it brought me to my current code editor, Neovim. Well today, I’m just going to show you what I use, what it looks like (at the current time of posting this), and how exactly do I get work done. </p>\n<h3>Theme</h3>\n<p>First things first, my color scheme. It’s called <code class=\"language-text\">gotham256</code>.</p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/ff418/simple.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 59.55662073097664%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"simple_screenshot\"\n        title=\"simple_screenshot\"\n        src=\"/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/b9e4f/simple.png\"\n        srcset=\"/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/cf440/simple.png 148w,\n/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/d2d38/simple.png 295w,\n/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/b9e4f/simple.png 590w,\n/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/f9b6a/simple.png 885w,\n/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/2d849/simple.png 1180w,\n/programitforward/static/8729f085e9d75674a858959ac5198828/ff418/simple.png 3338w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>Honestly, I like it. Nice and clean, nothing crazy. I really prefer to use  this theme cause it goes well with the syntax highlighting. I can be very picky especially when it comes to Typescript, Javascript, CSS, or even JSX. </p>\n<h3>Plugins</h3>\n<p>As for plugins, I use this list with <a href=\"https://github.com/junegunn/vim-plug\">vim-plug</a> as my plugin manager. Now I think I have a lot of plugins but please don’t judge. It makes my Neovim setup feel soooooo good when I program. </p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/3b243/plugins.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 128.515625%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"plugin_list\"\n        title=\"plugin_list\"\n        src=\"/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/b9e4f/plugins.png\"\n        srcset=\"/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/cf440/plugins.png 148w,\n/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/d2d38/plugins.png 295w,\n/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/b9e4f/plugins.png 590w,\n/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/f9b6a/plugins.png 885w,\n/programitforward/static/a418baf57d817a6e63a4f0320a702e3c/3b243/plugins.png 1024w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<h3>The Keyboard</h3>\n<p>So I have actually challenged myself to use the actual keybindings of Vim. Meaning…no arrow keys. Yupp, I made sure to turn off the arrow keys and just use HJKL. I’ve already become accustomed to the bindings that I don’t really adjust it as much. </p>\n<h3>Location</h3>\n<p>The sub title might be a little wierd and misleading but what I mean is where in my computer do I use Neovim. Do I use it in a Terminal or a GUI? I use Terminal all day, every day. Literally. I do everything in my terminal so whats the point of doing my programming in the GUI. </p>\n<p>Here is my entire setup. Since I’m on a Mac (No I am not a Apple fan boy. More of a Linux but stuck with Mac), I use iTerm2, Tmux, and Neovim. Screenshot as proof. </p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/82b63/editor.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"editor_in_charge\"\n        title=\"editor_in_charge\"\n        src=\"/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/b9e4f/editor.png\"\n        srcset=\"/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/cf440/editor.png 148w,\n/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/d2d38/editor.png 295w,\n/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/b9e4f/editor.png 590w,\n/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/f9b6a/editor.png 885w,\n/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/2d849/editor.png 1180w,\n/programitforward/static/e28e129300c441798b34762a844d8dec/82b63/editor.png 3360w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p><span\n      class=\"gatsby-resp-image-wrapper\"\n      style=\"position: relative; display: block; margin-left: auto; margin-right: auto;  max-width: 590px;\"\n    >\n      <a\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-link\"\n    href=\"/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/82b63/tmux.png\"\n    style=\"display: block\"\n    target=\"_blank\"\n    rel=\"noopener\"\n  >\n    <span\n    class=\"gatsby-resp-image-background-image\"\n    style=\"padding-bottom: 62.5%; position: relative; bottom: 0; left: 0; background-image: url('data:image/png;base64,'); background-size: cover; display: block;\"\n  ></span>\n  <img\n        class=\"gatsby-resp-image-image\"\n        alt=\"tmux_screen\"\n        title=\"tmux_screen\"\n        src=\"/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/b9e4f/tmux.png\"\n        srcset=\"/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/cf440/tmux.png 148w,\n/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/d2d38/tmux.png 295w,\n/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/b9e4f/tmux.png 590w,\n/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/f9b6a/tmux.png 885w,\n/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/2d849/tmux.png 1180w,\n/programitforward/static/88b0297b18b3d66080b90853d8550a79/82b63/tmux.png 3360w\"\n        sizes=\"(max-width: 590px) 100vw, 590px\"\n        loading=\"lazy\"\n      />\n  </a>\n    </span></p>\n<p>So yeah, this is my neovim editor setup. If you want a setup similar to mine, here is a link to my <a href=\"https://gist.github.com/joselevelsup/7907041b4f7c07dc74a02bca925a5b0c\">init.vim</a></p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Neovim Setup","date":"September 16, 2019","description":"joselevelsup's Neovim Setup"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"slug":"/the-neovim-setup/","previous":{"fields":{"slug":"/gitting-gud/"},"frontmatter":{"title":"Gitting Gud with Git"}},"next":null}}}